{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17647672","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17647672"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T20:46:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T20:46:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18258"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18258","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18258"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10972"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79295"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10972","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10972"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18258"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64617"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"7235"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25493"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25496"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27138"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79295","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79295"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe obturator nerve originates from the lumbar plexus and gives sensory and motor innervation to the lower limb. One of the muscles that it innervates provides both hip adduction and knee flexion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is this muscle?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adductor brevis","Adductor longus","Adductor magnus","Gracilis","Obturator externus"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe obturator nerve is a major nerve of the lumbar plexus that innervates muscles in the medial compartment of the thigh. These muscles are primarily responsible for hip adduction.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Egracilis\u003C/strong\u003E muscle is innervated by the obturator nerve and is involved in both hip adduction and knee flexion. It is part of the medial compartment of the thigh.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EObturator externus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is innervated by the obturator nerve but is primarily involved in lateral rotation of the hip.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdductor longus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is involved in hip adduction but not knee flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdductor brevis\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is involved in hip adduction but not knee flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdductor magnus\u003C/strong\u003E - This muscle is involved in hip adduction but not knee flexion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The obturator nerve innervates muscles in the medial compartment of the thigh, primarily responsible for hip adduction.","The gracilis muscle is innervated by the obturator nerve and is involved in both hip adduction and knee flexion.","The obturator nerve arises from the lumbar plexus, specifically from the L2, L3, and L4 nerve roots."],"references":["Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2018). Textbook of Orthopaedics, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Singh, V. (2018). Textbook of Anatomy Abdomen and Lower Limb; Volume II (Vol. 2). Elsevier Health Sciences","Cantrell AJ, Imonugo O, Varacallo M. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Leg Bones. [Updated 2023 Aug 14]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537024/","Raftery A. General Anatomy and Musculoskeletal System. Ann R Coll Surg Engl. 2006 Jul;88(4):425. doi: 10.1308/003588406X114802d. PMCID: PMC1964629","Chaudhry SR, Nahian A, Chaudhry K. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis, Pelvis. [Updated 2023 Jul 25]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK482258/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64617"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18258"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64617","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64617"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-14T08:01:12+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-14T08:02:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10972"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79295"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedA